            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "TL;DR: In the refactoring of #38525, the generic JSON-RPC implementation will turn `ClientToServer` and `ServerToClient` into `string` because these two types are LSP-based. However, if we leave a compatibility layer for the current `lsp.rpc`, we can also fix this issue.\n\nThis is quite misleading. In JSON-RPC protocol terminology, a client always sends a request with a method, and the server always returns a response. However, our JSON-RPC \"client\" can actually function as both a client (sending requests) and a server (responding to requests). I suspect it was named \"client\" simply due to the influence of LSP; an LSP client and server do not align with JSON-RPC roles, as both act as both client and server in JSON-RPC. I have renamed our RPC \"client\" to \"peer\" in that draft PR, which I hope makes things clearer. I believe the misunderstanding stems from naming the RPC functionality \"client\", but it's sometimes a server, depending on its behavior.\n\nI have also renamed `notification` to `on_notify` and `server_request` to `on_request` to indicate that we are receiving actions when they are triggered. This may distinguish them from `notify` and `request`, which represent actions we initiate.",
