            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> In JSON-RPC protocol terminology, a client always sends a request with a method, and the server always returns a response. However, our JSON-RPC \"client\" can actually function as both a client (sending requests) and a server (responding to requests).\n\nThis is often the case in network programming that both sides could initiate a request. The JSON-RPC spec also alludes to this:\n\n> One implementation of this specification could easily fill both of those roles, even at the same time, to other different clients or the same client. This specification does not address that layer of complexity.\n\nThe Client and Server terminology is still useful. It clarifies who's listening to connections, and who is initiating the connection. And based on the context in which the JSON-RPC mechanism is used it also clarifies the role's of the two sides.\nIf you take a look at various existing JSON-RPC libraries you'll also find that most do use Client and Server terms exactly for that purpose.\n\nWhile \"peer\" as term is useful to refer to the other side, I think abstracting away client/server completely is making things less clear - because it makes it harder to reason about which is which.",
