            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> While \"peer\" as term is useful to refer to the other side, I think abstracting away client/server completely is making things less clear - because it makes it harder to reason about which is which.\n\nI mean that the JSON-RPC protocol defines client and server very clearly because JSON-RPC itself is a stateless, connectionless protocol. This nature also means that each distinction between client and server (in the JSON-RPC sense) is limited to a single connection. However, the JSON-RPC objects we maintain are stateful; in any single request, it only plays one roleâ€”either client or serverâ€”but throughout its entire lifecycle, its role within JSON-RPC can switch.\n\n> If you take a look at various existing JSON-RPC libraries you'll also find that most do use Client and Server terms exactly for that purpose.\n\nThis is not correct. I just did some research: JavaScript's [`json-rpc-2.0`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/json-rpc-2.0) provides `JSONRPCServer` and `JSONRPCClient`, but for objects that have bidirectional request capabilities, it calls them `JSONRPCServerAndClient`. Meanwhile, Go's [`sourcegraph/jsonrpc2`](https://github.com/sourcegraph/jsonrpc2) only provides `Conn`, which is also bidirectional. I also looked at some other JSON-RPC libraries; they provide both `server` and `client` with non-overlapping functions and no bidirectional sending capabilities. In `vscode-jsonrpc`, the library used to support VS Code's LSP implementation, there is only a type named `MessageConnection` that facilitates bidirectional request.\n\nI believe our code already reflects the problems caused by this somewhat misleading naming, and the incorrect annotation in this issue is a perfect example. Furthermore, I previously noticed that the `cmd` passed to `vim.lsp.config` can be `fun(dispatchers: vim.lsp.rpc.Dispatchers, config: vim.lsp.ClientConfig): vim.lsp.rpc.Client`. This confused me at the time because I thought I should pass a function that creates a complete LSP client, but in fact, it's to create a new client that functions as an LSP server.\n\nIf `peer` is not clear enough, it could perhaps be called `connection`.",
